Question: Which of the following LaTeX code snippets correctly implements a right brace to group x and y as equal to a, while keeping z separate, in a cases environment?

A) \begin{cases}
     x \\
     y \right\} = a \\
     z = b
   \end{cases}

B) \begin{cases}
     \left. \begin{array}{c}
     x \\
     y
     \end{array} \right\rbrace = a \\
     z = b
   \end{cases}

C) \begin{cases}
     x \\
     y \\
     \left\rbrace = a \\
     z = b
   \end{cases}

D) \begin{cases}
     x \\
     y \} = a \\
     z = b
   \end{cases}

Correct Answer: B

Explanation: Option B is correct because it properly uses the \left. and \right\rbrace commands to create a right brace that groups x and y together. The \begin{array}{c} environment ensures proper vertical alignment. Options A, C, and D all have syntax errors or improper brace placement that would not compile correctly or achieve the desired grouping effect.

